				<table width="100%" cellspacing="5">
				<tr>
					<td>
					

						<div class="postbody"><div class="quotetitle">Gilbert wrote:</div><div class="quotecontent">I think not being able to change vertical position mid-frame is a huge bummer (together with the inability to flip sprites of course) for the SMS. Many games cannot have an informative status bar because of this(especially for games that have vertical scrolling obviously) and have to rely on sprites to display the scores on screen, whereas most of the other information such as remaining number of lives, etc. are missing, forcing players to press PAUSE for vital information.</div><br />Platformers can usually get away with delayed vertical scrolling in order to have more complete status bars. It worked beautifully for the Mickey Mouse games, which are some of the best in the platform, IMO.<br /><br /><div class="quotetitle"><b>Quote:</b></div><div class="quotecontent">A lot of their games had impressive (at the time) parallax scrolling floor(what will also be used in the arcade game Street Fighter II), especially early games such as Hokuto no Ken and Transbot, which also extended to the Mega Drive versions of Hokuto no Ken (again) and Altered Beast.</div><br /><a href="https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=d3Uw_ZdBBlg" class="postlink">Aladdin</a> has some of the best effects I've ever seen in an 8-bit game, completing the parallax effect with 3D walls. This only goes on for the first 2 levels it seems, the rest of the game is much more &quot;normal&quot;.</div>

